Wish I could give "NO STARS". We purchased three, 12 pc. Place settings of dishes in bisque at Macy's  stone town store. When the where delivered to our home in Las Vegas today, we opened the boxes only to find out that the dishes shipped were gray. What incompetent people. No wonder why Macys has so many issues.  

Second part of stupid; 

So we took the incorrect dishes to the home store to exchange them for the correct ones. When we got to Macys we looked at the correct color and did the exchange and also purchase additional dishes to go with the set. Talk about stupid, when we got home we had the damn gray dishes again. The associate gave us the dishes that we returned with the additional purchase. Now we have to go back for a second time to return the wrong dishes again. These people at Macy's are so incompetent is almost funny. Retail workers need to pay attention to what they are paid to do!!

(Part 1 of 2)

I looked upon our dinner at Giada De Laurentiis' new signature restaurant with much anticipation, people call weeks if not months in advance for reservations. We asked for window seating in order to see the Bellagio fountains and I forgot to slip the hostess a little extra dinero to get the optimum view.  The six of us were snuggled up cozy in a booth that would ordinarily swallow up two patrons, but still close enough to the action to see what was going on.  It was mild enough that evening to open the windows and show off their "al fresco" feature but I doubt that anyone would expect the piercing shrill of a passing emergency vehicle's siren to be so loud...

The cocktails seem to be on the colorful fruity side named after films in association with Giada's grandfather Dino De Laurentiis, not that the films were whimsical but only the drinks association with them, and maybe the iPads showcasing them.  I ordered a non-alcoholic Arnold Palmer that came along with its own pitcher, very stylish indeed.  In fact, there is no shortage of Giada's personal touches and branding throughout, even the hand towels in the restrooms felt lux, but it is her comfortable, more casual style that really comes out which also distinguishes the restaurant from places like Thomas Kellar's Bouchon, or Guy Savoy's eponymous restaurant at Caesar's...

It's nice to have six people instead of only two, that way you can share (steal) more things from your dinner guests.  Two people went for the four course nightly prix fixe and the other four merely obliged by ordering four individual courses a la carte.  The prix fixe is $120 per person and it comes with an autographed picture and recipes in a nice portfolio.  The bread service is fancy but I didn't think it was overly ostentatious;  try the Rosemary Focaccia, it's like cornbread...

Appetizers:
- Orzo Meatballs;
- Frito Misto Shrimp & Calamari;
- Bacon Wrapped Dates;
- Peppers & Goat Cheese;
- Ahi Crostini;
- Prosciutto;
- Wood Roasted Mushrooms;

No losers here but the meatballs are really good and are the only really must haves because they are the most uniquely Giada dish from this list.  The dates are good too but when dates are in season I've seen them elsewhere.  The fried squid, prosciutto, and peppers are not as interesting and more on the pedestrian side.  The Ahi Crostini may have been off menu just for the prix fixe, it was interesting with the inclusion of a sliced gherkin for a touch of sweet/sour taste;  the mushrooms are earthy with umami flavor but seem more appropriate as a side...

In-between courses they served us complementary aperitivo.  I don't remember what it was, I don't think its Campari since that's usually red tinged and this was clear;  reminded me of gin...

Pasta:
- Lobster Ravioli;
- Crab & Scallop Risotto;
- Shrimp Lemon Spaghetti;

The two prix fixes came with the spaghetti, so we balanced the table out with two orders each of the ravioli and the risotto.  I was so glad that everyone at the table had a formal pasta course, it allowed us to share one of the strongest points of Giada's: the fresh pasta.  The shrimp spaghetti is uber rich with copious amounts of cream and butter with lemon zest.  The colossal shrimp might even be UT-6 count. Not to be outdone is the crab and scallop risotto with a pair of marshmallow sized scallop.  The crab presence is not lost to the scallop and there are even asparagus.  Again, there is a generous amount of EVOO and butter.  The lobster ravioli would be right up there with the spaghetti and the risotto if there weren't a couple of ravioli that had lobster shells in them...

(End of Part 1)
